'''Rudolph Franz Zallinger''' (November 12, 1919 – August 1, 1995) was an American-based [[Austrians|Austrian]]-[[Russians|Russian]] artist notable for his mural ''[[The Age of Reptiles]]'' (1947) at [[Yale University]]'s [[Peabody Museum of Natural History]]. His painting of ''[[Tyrannosaurus]]'' heavily influenced the creature design of [[Toho Studios]]' ''[[Godzilla (1954 film)|Godzilla]]'' (1954). Two of Zallinger's dinosaurs, ''T. rex'' and ''[[Brontosaurus]]'', are seen in the film as part of a slide demonstration during a lecture in the [[National Diet Building]]. A third slide showing Zallinger's ''[[Stegosaurus]]'' was planned but eventually not used in the film.
==Biography== Zallinger was born in [[Irkutsk]], [[Siberia]] in 1919. He attended [[Yale School of Art|Yale's School of Fine Arts]] on scholarships during the [[Great Depression]], was trained as an illustrator, and he taught at Yale after graduation. The Peabody Museum hired him to paint the mural in 1943 at $40 a week, and Zallinger took a crash course in paleontology to prepare for the job. The mural is one of the largest in the world, measuring 110 feet (33.5 meters) by 16 feet (4.9 meters). It required more than 4.5 years (1943–1947) to complete.<ref name="peabody.yale.edu">{{Cite web | last = | first = | title = Rudolph Franz Zallinger | url = http://peabody.yale.edu/collections/archives/biography/rudolph-franz-zallinger | publisher =Yale Peabody Museum: Collections : Archives | date = | accessdate = 25 March 2012 }}</ref> A portion of the mural appeared on a United States postage stamp in 1970.<ref name="Stamp">{{Cite web | last = | first = | title = 1970 U.S. Postage Stamp Issues | url = http://www.1847us.com/ByYear/1970.htm | publisher =1847us.com | date =2011 | accessdate = 25 March 2012 }}</ref> After that, the museum appointed him as the “artist in residence”, a position he held until his death.<ref name="Wallace2004">{{cite book|author=Wallace, D.R.|title=Beasts of Eden|publisher=[[University of California Press]]|year=2004|isbn=0-520-23731-5}}</ref>
Zallinger received many assignments, prominent among which are those he did for illustrating articles for [[Life (magazine)|Life]] magazines. His paintings portrayed dinosaurs, the [[Russian Revolution]], the rain forests of Dutch Guiana (now [[Suriname]]) and the [[Minoan civilization|Minoan]]s of ancient [[Crete]], besides others.<ref name="peabody.yale.edu"/>
He taught at the Yale School of Fine Arts, the Hartford Art School at the University of Hartford in West Hartford, and at the Paier School of Art in Hamden.<ref name="peabody.yale.edu"/>
==Other prominent works of Zallinger== * ''The Age of Mammals'' — a {{convert|60|by|5|ft|m}} [[fresco-secco]] mural, painted from 1961 to 1967, now displayed on the south wall of the Yale Peabody Museum of Natural History.<ref name="AgeOfMammals">{{cite web|url=http://peabody.yale.edu/exhibits/age-mammals-mural |title=The Age of Mammals mural|website=Yale Peabody Museum of Natural History}}</ref> * ''[[March of Progress]]'' (1965) — a popular illustration and one of the world's most recognizable scientific images.
